IV. useRef()
---------------------------
. It is commonly used to access a DOM element (like a button, input, or div) and manipulate DOM elements
. It is not needing to set up state or use useEffect.
. useRef() returns an object with a 'current' property, we use 'current' property to get the value.

syntax:
 const myRef = useRef(initialValue);

---------------------------
Example1: Add event
---------------------------
 import React, { useRef } from 'react';

function App() {
  const inputRef = useRef(null);

  const focusInput = () => {
    inputRef.current.focus(); // Focus the input field when the button is clicked
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <input type="text" ref={inputRef} placeholder="Focus me" />
      <button onClick={focusInput}>Focus on Input</button>
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;

